  "prompt": "Is magnesium considered a solid, liquid or gas and why?",
  "response": "Magnesium is considered a solid at room temperature. This is because it has a melting point of about 650 degrees Celsius (1202 degrees Fahrenheit), which is much higher than typical room temperature. At room temperature, magnesium exists in a solid state with a crystalline structure. It is a light, silvery-white metal that is relatively soft and malleable. It only transitions to a liquid when heated to its melting point and becomes a gas when it reaches its boiling point of approximately 1107 degrees Celsius (2025 degrees Fahrenheit).",
